   =20
 =20
Let=E2=80=99s say that you are a giant universal investor and you own 10% o=
f every company in the world. The chief executive officer=C2=A0of one of yo=
ur portfolio companies, a US oil and gas exploration and production busines=
s, calls you up and says =E2=80=9Chey, oil prices are really high, I want t=
o drill a bunch of wells and ramp up production to sell lots of oil at $120=
 a barrel, whaddaya think?=E2=80=9D What do you think?Here are some things =
that you might say to this CEO, specifically because you are a giant univer=
sal investor and you own 10% of every company in the world:=09Look: I own 1=
0% of your company, but I also own 10% of every other oil driller. They=E2=
=80=99re all going to call me up and say the same thing: =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=
=99s drill more oil.=E2=80=9D If I say yes to all of them, the volume of oi=
l production will go up, but the price will go down. Everyone will drill mo=
re oil and sell it for less money, and we=E2=80=99ll all be worse off. Sure=
 if=C2=A0only you=C2=A0drilled more oil=C2=A0you=C2=A0would make more money=
, but I own all of your competitors, so I can=E2=80=99t think in those term=
s. If everyone drilled more oil, no one would make more money. And in fact =
in the last big oil boom, everyone did drill more oil, and it cost public i=
nvestors like me hundreds of billions of dollars. So, no.=09Look: I own 10%=
 of your company, but I also own 10% of every beachfront hotel company, and=
 of every other company in the world for that matter. More oil drilling wil=
l make you more money, sure, but it will also cause more global warming, wh=
ich will cause lots of economic destruction and instability. As a universal=
 investor, I am paid primarily to think about systemic=C2=A0risks, not to c=
are about the operations of any one company. The systemic risks to my portf=
olio=C2=A0from the=C2=A0global warming will be much greater than the profit=
s to me from you drilling a bit more=C2=A0oil, so I am philosophically tryi=
ng to transition all my portfolio companies away from fossil-fuel extractio=
n.[1] So, no.If there are enough investors like you =E2=80=94=C2=A0enough i=
nvestors who own the oil sector as a whole and so don=E2=80=99t want any on=
e player to be undisciplined about production, or enough investors who care=
 about environmental risks=C2=A0and so get nervous about making long-term i=
nvestments in oil production =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the CEO will abandon her p=
lans to drill more oil. After all, you investors are the people who buy her=
 stock, who approve her bonuses, who will keep her in power if an activist =
shows up trying to fire her. She wants to do what you want, and if that mea=
ns drilling less oil (and making less money) then that=E2=80=99s what she=
=E2=80=99ll do. Her ultimate goal is shareholder happiness, not profit maxi=
mization.But an oil company that=C2=A0isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0owned by universal=
 owners =E2=80=94=C2=A0one that is owned by people whose wealth is concentr=
ated in that single oil company =E2=80=94=C2=A0might make different decisio=
ns. And so:Harold Hamm, the billionaire fracking pioneer who helped launch =
the U.S. shale boom, is looking to take Continental Resources Inc. private,=
 offering about $4.3 billion in cash to buy the portion of the company=E2=
=80=99s shares he and his family don=E2=80=99t already own. =E2=80=A6While =
most of Continental=E2=80=99s publicly traded oil-company peers are owned b=
y multiple institutional investors, Mr. Hamm, the 13th child of Oklahoma sh=
arecroppers, has retained control of the company he founded in 1967, holdin=
g north of 70% of its shares even after it went public in 2007, according t=
o FactSet. =E2=80=A6In a statement to employees, Mr. Hamm said it no longer=
 makes sense for Continental to be a publicly traded company, citing =E2=80=
=9Ca lack of support from the public market=E2=80=9D for oil-and-gas compan=
ies, evident in the diminishing number of public shale companies due to acq=
uisitions and bankruptcies, and with some going private.The Financial Times=
 elaborates:Shale baron Harold Hamm has hardly hidden his disdain for Wall =
Street=E2=80=99s environmental, social and governance movement, considering=
 it a leash on companies such as Continental Resources as they try to get o=
n with the job of producing more fossil fuels.A climate change =E2=80=9Crel=
igion=E2=80=9D had gripped investors, he argued in an interview with the Fi=
nancial Times last year, and companies such as European supermajor BP were =
about to =E2=80=9Ccut their [own] throat=E2=80=9D by winding down oil opera=
tions under pressure to decarbonise. ...Analysts said the move could free C=
ontinental to do what public producers have for months been told by Wall St=
reet not to: fire up drilling rigs to capitalise on a surge in oil prices t=
o well above $100 a barrel.Hamm and other public shale bosses watched as th=
eir privately held rivals sharply escalated drilling activity this year, un=
bothered by institutional investors insisting on scooping up their piece of=
 the windfall.Executives have often seethed in private about their difficul=
ties in persuading ESG-focused portfolio managers in long-only funds to bac=
k more oil and gas exploration.The obvious move here is to blame ESG: ESG-f=
ocused public investors don=E2=80=99t want to drill for oil, so they hold b=
ack oil drillers, but if you go private you can avoid ESG constraints. Shal=
e barons and ESG investors are sort of natural enemies, so it is no surpris=
e that Hamm doesn=E2=80=99t like ESG.But we have been  talking for years ar=
ound here about the  other possible theory: Index funds that own every (pub=
lic) company in an industry, the theory goes, constrain competition, becaus=
e if everyone ramps up production to steal market share then everybody lose=
s, and universal owners are a way to coordinate to restrict competition and=
 keep margins high. The shale drilling boom is  an infamous case of how hig=
h oil prices led to overinvestment in drilling and ultimately to huge losse=
s for investors. Public investors learned that lesson really well. =E2=80=
=9CShale Oil=E2=80=99s Newfound Production Discipline Begins to Pay Off,=E2=
=80=9D  said a Bloomberg headline last year. If you own every oil company, =
it is insane to encourage all of them to drill more wells, not as a climate=
 matter, just as a profitability matter. But if you own=C2=A0one=C2=A0oil c=
ompany, that is the opportunity.By the way: If you are an ESG-focused inves=
tor, and you=C2=A0do=C2=A0own shares of a public oil company, and that oil =
company=E2=80=99s CEO says =E2=80=9Cbeing owned by ESG-focused public share=
holders is holding us back, I=E2=80=99ve raised some money, let=E2=80=99s g=
o private=E2=80=9D: Should you vote to approve the deal?[2] (This is less r=
elevant to Continental, where Hamm=E2=80=99s family owns a large majority o=
f the stock, but it=E2=80=99s a fun general question.[3]) On the one hand, =
if the company goes private, you=C2=A0are (1) reducing the carbon emissions=
 of your portfolio and (2) getting bought out at a premium. On the other ha=
nd, you are (1) definitely increasing the amount of carbon emissions=C2=A0i=
n the world, since the company is going private specifically in order to po=
llute more, and (2) missing out on the profits of doing that. An ESG strate=
gy of =E2=80=9Cwe will own all the oil companies, to prevent someone worse =
from owning the oil companies=E2=80=9D makes a weird kind of sense.
