In a former life,=C2=A0I used to structure and market derivatives to corpor=
ate clients at Goldman Sachs Group Inc. (Disclosure!) Some basic themes of =
derivatives marketing are:=09When markets are boring and volatility is low,=
 it is easy and customer-friendly to go around to customers and offer to bu=
y some options from them. =E2=80=9CWe will give you cash for the volatility=
 of your stock, which you weren=E2=80=99t using anyway,=E2=80=9D is the bas=
ic pitch, which is very appealing to customers who are bored because the ma=
rket isn=E2=80=99t doing anything. This is, like, covered-call strategies f=
or asset owners, or put-writing strategies for corporate stock buybacks, et=
c.=09When markets are scary and volatility is high, it is easy and customer=
-friendly to go around to customers and offer to sell them some options. =
=E2=80=9CYou can pay us a little bit of money for insurance from this scary=
 market,=E2=80=9D is the basic pitch, which is very appealing to customers =
who are scared because the market keeps going down.=C2=A0=09It is always be=
tter=C2=A0not=C2=A0to ask the customer for a cash payment up front. (This m=
akes Method 2 harder.) If you can structure a fee into the product without =
an explicit price, that is better.=09The best derivatives=C2=A0products do =
not contain, or even hint at, words like =E2=80=9Cderivative=E2=80=9D or =
=E2=80=9Coption=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cput=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ccall.=E2=80=
=9D With the best derivatives products, you walk into the room and have an =
hourlong meeting with the client and discuss the product in detail and they=
 understand it perfectly and you shake hands and they look at your business=
 card and say =E2=80=9Cwait you=E2=80=99re a derivatives salesperson?=E2=80=
=9D The best products identify the customer=E2=80=99s needs or insecurities=
 and give her a solution to them that feels simple and natural; sure=C2=A0y=
ou know that the thing is a series of puts and calls that your quants can m=
odel, but to the=C2=A0client=C2=A0it doesn=E2=80=99t feel that way at all.I=
n that vein,  I love this:Goldman Sachs Group Inc. is preparing to offer fo=
reign-exchange prices that last for days to help fintechs, airlines and e-c=
ommerce firms avoid turbulence in the $6.6 trillion-per-day global currency=
 market.The Wall Street giant has begun quoting FX rates that last for minu=
tes and plans to extend this in the coming weeks, according to Abbas Khamis=
a, executive director in FX solutions and structuring at the bank. The aim =
is to help firms hedge risk and protect them from having to do hundreds of =
transactions at different rates. =E2=80=A6Under Goldman=E2=80=99s offering,=
 clients can expect to pay a premium, in the form of an added spread, to re=
flect the risk that exchange rates move against the bank=E2=80=99s position=
. The bank will vary its prices based on the volumes, currency pairs and am=
ount of time the customer needs.=E2=80=9CFirms can request a quote ranging =
from minutes to hours, to days, to the weekend and eventually to months, wi=
th clients knowing exactly how much they are being charged,=E2=80=9D Khamis=
a said in an interview. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve had a lot of interest.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=A6Goldman=E2=80=99s guaranteed prices are different to forw=
ard rates because they give clients the flexibility to trade at a set rate =
rather than requiring them to do so, Khamisa said. =E2=80=9CWhen the client=
 has certainty on the timings and notional of their exposure, then they can=
 execute a trade,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThis allows clients to price t=
heir goods and services in multiple currencies, without the challenges of f=
orecasting and risk managing potential exposures in advance.=E2=80=9DOne so=
rt of imagines the mandate: =E2=80=9COkay, implied volatility is up, let=E2=
=80=99s go out and sell some short-dated puts and calls.=E2=80=9D If you go=
 to a client and say, like, =E2=80=9Chi, are you in the market for a two-ho=
ur call option on 10 million pounds,=E2=80=9D they will say =E2=80=9Chuh th=
at sounds like a weird thing, probably not.=E2=80=9D[4] But if you go to th=
e client and say =E2=80=9Cas your special relationship bank, we will give y=
ou a guaranteed price on up to 10 million pounds for the next two hours,=C2=
=A0so you can price your goods in multiple currencies without the challenge=
s of forecasting and risk managing potential exposures in advance, for two =
hours,=E2=80=9D the client will find that very convenient and appreciate yo=
ur good service.=C2=A0I am not sure how pricing works exactly, but the way =
I read this story is that the client is not charged an upfront fee: =E2=80=
=9CClients can expect to pay a premium, in the form of an added spread,=E2=
=80=9D meaning that you pay for the option only if (and to the extent) you =
exercise it. That is a somewhat nervous-making approach, for the bank. In t=
heory, if you tell the client =E2=80=9Cyou can buy as many as 10 million po=
unds, or as few as zero pounds, for $1.20 each over the next hour, and you =
just pay us an extra $0.001 for each pound you end up buying,=E2=80=9D[5]=
=C2=A0then that is effectively a call option on 10 million pounds, struck a=
t $1.201, that you have given away for free. If the pound goes above $1.201=
 during that hour, the client should buy all 10 million pounds from you, an=
d you will have lost money; if the pound stays below $1.201, the client sho=
uld go buy its pounds elsewhere =E2=80=94=C2=A0plenty of banks are happy to=
 sell pounds at the spot price=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and you will not make mo=
ney.[6] This is a terrible trade, for the bank, if the client is a purely r=
ational economic actor.On the other hand there are good reasons to think th=
e client will not be a purely rational economic actor. =E2=80=9CThe aim is =
to help firms hedge risk and protect them from having to do hundreds of tra=
nsactions at different rates.=E2=80=9D There probably are lots of clients w=
ho will happily pay a higher average rate to not have to worry about it. Th=
e client is explicitly paying you for the relief of not having to monitor t=
he FX market. If the pound goes up, the client buys from you and underpays.=
 If the pound goes down, the client buys from you and overpays but is happy=
 not to have to think about it. If the pound goes up and down and up and do=
wn, the client buys from you the whole time; sure, the client could buy fro=
m you when it=E2=80=99s up and from another broker when it=E2=80=99s down, =
but that is a lot of work, and the client is cheerfully paying you to avoid=
 that work. Just putting the =E2=80=9Chundreds of transactions at different=
 rates=E2=80=9D into a spreadsheet is work, and the client will pay somethi=
ng to avoid that.Also of course if some=C2=A0clients do keep buying from yo=
u when the pound is up, and not when it is down, then you will stop offerin=
g them this service. This is a good-long-term-relationship sort of service,=
 not a series of economically priced options.Still you have to make sure no=
t to sign up the clients who are=C2=A0purely rational economic actors, and =
who will put in the work to hose you:Tom Auld, a Cambridge University acade=
mic and former high frequency trader, said the plans would likely suit both=
 sides -- provided clients are meeting corporate needs and aren=E2=80=99t b=
etting on market moves.=E2=80=9CIt makes a lot of sense if you=E2=80=99ve g=
ot an unsophisticated client who is not going to try and arbitrage the pric=
e, and may not be able to make a quick decision,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=
=9CGoldman Sachs will have to be very careful about who they field it to. T=
hey won=E2=80=99t give it to a hedge fund but they might give it to an SME =
or some other client that isn=E2=80=99t interested in arbitraging.=E2=80=9D=
Yeah. If you are a derivatives structurer and you say to your boss, =E2=80=
=9Clet=E2=80=99s write free options to small corporate clients,=E2=80=9D yo=
ur boss will hear you out; writing free options to small businesses can be =
lucrative. Nobody lasts long writing free options to hedge funds.
