      Oracle latency
   =20
 =20
We  talked a few weeks ago about differences in how the traditional financi=
al system and the crypto financial system treat leverage. The way the tradi=
tional system works is that if you have a margin loan, and the value of you=
r collateral declines, your broker calls you up and says =E2=80=9Chey we ne=
ed more collateral,=E2=80=9D and you either post more collateral and it=E2=
=80=99s fine, or you don=E2=80=99t post more collateral and your broker liq=
uidates your position. Or sometimes you say something like =E2=80=9Chang on=
 I=E2=80=99ve got another call,  I=E2=80=99ll call you back after lunch,=E2=
=80=9D or =E2=80=9Csorry I don=E2=80=99t have the money right now but I am =
a good customer and you know I=E2=80=99m good for it,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9C=
I don=E2=80=99t have the money right now but I=E2=80=99m pretty sure prices=
 can only recover from here so why don=E2=80=99t you let it ride for a day =
or two,=E2=80=9D or whatever, and you don=E2=80=99t post more collateral bu=
t your broker=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0liquidate your position because you=
=E2=80=99re a human and your broker is a human and everyone is embedded in =
a repeated social game with fuzzy rules. Whereas the way that the crypto sy=
stem =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularly the decentralized finance side of it =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0works is that if you have a margin loan, and the value of your =
collateral declines far enough, a robot liquidates the collateral immediate=
ly without even bothering to call you.=C2=A0There are advantages and disadv=
antages to each approach. We were talking about a proposal from crypto exch=
ange FTX, and I wrote:Simplistically, you=E2=80=99d expect the FTX model to=
 lead to=C2=A0more=C2=A0defaults and liquidations, but for those defaults t=
o be=C2=A0less bad. In the traditional system, sometimes people will have a=
 =E2=80=9Ctechnical issue,=E2=80=9D and the exchange will =E2=80=9Cgive the=
 appropriate amount of time not to dislocate the market and create a bigger=
 stress on that,=E2=80=9D and it will work out fine =E2=80=94=C2=A0but occa=
sionally it=C2=A0won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0work out fine, and by delaying the exch=
ange will have caused a much bigger problem.Often, delaying liquidation wil=
l just make the problem go away: Prices will recover and you won=E2=80=99t =
have to liquidate. Sometimes, delaying liquidation will make the problem wo=
rse: Prices will keep going down, and by the time you liquidate there won=
=E2=80=99t be enough value left to repay the margin loan.Part of this is ab=
out the fuzziness of the traditional system, but part of it is also about m=
easurement times. In traditional finance, often, you get margin calls based=
 on the price of your assets at the end of the day, or at some other discre=
te measuring time. If your stocks go down in the morning and back up in the=
 afternoon, you might be undercollateralized at noon, but you never get a m=
argin call because it=E2=80=99s all fine by the time your broker gets aroun=
d to looking at the report at 4:30. FTX=E2=80=99s proposal, and the crypto =
ethos generally, is about real-time 24/7 monitoring and automatic liquidati=
ons. I wrote:In the traditional system, if the price of corn drops at midni=
ght, and your broker calls you up for more margin, and you don=E2=80=99t po=
st more margin, your broker thinks =E2=80=9Caha you are asleep=E2=80=9D and=
 waits until the morning to call you again. But =E2=80=9Chumans are asleep =
at midnight=E2=80=9D is the sort of off-chain information that a purely alg=
orithmic approach would ignore.Well! At FT Alphaville, Alexandra Scaggs has=
 a fun post about oracle latency. A large crypto wallet owns a lot of Ether=
eum, funded by borrowing, and as the price of Ethereum dropped the account =
became undercollateralized and should have been liquidated. But it wasn=E2=
=80=99t. Scaggs:On Wednesday morning, the price of ether fell below the imp=
lied liquidation price. At the time that was said to be around $1,015.So wh=
at happened? Why didn=E2=80=99t the account get liquidated?As the above twe=
et explains, it was an issue of =E2=80=9Coracle update latency=E2=80=9D. =
=E2=80=A6 At risk of oversimplification, an =E2=80=9Coracle=E2=80=9D is ess=
entially a data feed that helps smart contracts perform their function. In =
this case a service called chainlink puts prices on the blockchain so Aave=
=E2=80=99s smart contracts can use them to operate.This isn=E2=80=99t the f=
utures market, and updating prices on-chain is expensive. So they aren=E2=
=80=99t refreshed in real time. Instead, chainlink updates the on-chain pri=
ces when the =E2=80=9Coff-chain=E2=80=9D data deviates by 0.5 per cent or m=
ore from the latest update, or every hour.When ether fell to around $1015, =
it would have triggered a sizable liquidation if it had met the criteria fo=
r the price to go on-chain.But it didn=E2=80=99t. It wasn=E2=80=99t a large=
 enough move compared to the price recorded in the prior on-chain update, a=
nd it didn=E2=80=99t last for an hour. So instead of getting blown out of a=
round $250mn in ether, the account got to live another day.I dunno. Seems f=
ine? =E2=80=9CWe check the prices every hour, and if you=E2=80=99re underco=
llateralized at any hourly update we=E2=80=99ll liquidate you=E2=80=9D is k=
ind of a reasonable thing for a broker to say. As a way to handle financial=
-market risk, it=E2=80=99s just fine; the lender takes an hour of price ris=
k, which is a lot less than lenders take=C2=A0in a lot of traditional finan=
cing businesses. Still it=E2=80=99s not a particularly, like,=C2=A0futurist=
ic=C2=A0thing for the=C2=A0broker to say? In the stock market, traders have=
 computers that can check the price many times each millisecond. In crypto,=
 the computers are famously slow and expensive, so checking the price every=
 hour is the best they can do.
