      Should index funds be illegal?
   =20
 =20
Or, rather, should index providers have to register as investment advisers =
and I guess be fiduciaries to the people who invest in index funds? Or some=
thing? Here=E2=80=99s a US Securities and Exchange Commission request for c=
omment:The Securities and Exchange Commission today announced that it is re=
questing information and public comment on matters related to the activitie=
s of certain =E2=80=9Cinformation providers,=E2=80=9D including whether, un=
der particular facts and circumstances, information providers are acting as=
 =E2=80=9Cinvestment advisers=E2=80=9D under the Investment Advisers Act of=
 1940 (=E2=80=9CAdvisers Act=E2=80=9D). The Request specifically focuses on=
 index providers, model portfolio providers, and pricing services.=E2=80=9C=
In recent decades, the use of information providers has grown, changing the=
 asset management industry,=E2=80=9D said SEC Chair Gary Gensler. =E2=80=9C=
The role of these information providers today raises important questions un=
der the securities laws as to when they are providing investment advice rat=
her than merely information. In order to help the Commission determine when=
=E2=80=94and under what facts and circumstances=E2=80=94these providers are=
 giving investment advice, the Commission seeks information and public comm=
ent to help guide our approach.=E2=80=9DI will say that, while I don=E2=80=
=99t really have a view on whether or how index providers should be regulat=
ed (and, disclosure, Bloomberg LP is in the index business), I do share the=
 SEC=E2=80=99s apparent instinct that big index providers are=C2=A0the most=
 important financial-market participants that=C2=A0aren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0subj=
ect to a lot of SEC oversight.=C2=A0
