fic proposal to the board is to do a tender offer followed by a short-form =
merger under Oklahoma law=C2=A0without a shareholder vote at all.[4] A well=
-known fact of finance is that a limit order is an option: If you say =E2=
=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll sell pounds at $1.20,=E2=80=9D then you have effectively=
 written a call option to the market struck at $1.20. This is a somewhat od=
d option to analyze, because in the ordinary course of most markets you can=
 cancel your limit orders at any time before someone trades with you (and i=
n some markets =E2=80=94=C2=A0those with =E2=80=9C last look,=E2=80=9D and =
indicative not-held broker markets for many assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0you can c=
ancel it after they try to trade, too). But if you explicitly agree with a =
customer that your market is good for an hour or a day or a weekend or a mo=
nth then that is simply a vanilla option.[5] Very fake numbers! I have not =
bothered to try to price this and have no idea if that is even the right or=
der of magnitude for a one-hour pound call option; nor do I know how Goldma=
n is pricing this thing.[6] Here I assume that you are not hedging the opti=
on; if you are hedging it according to a Black-Scholes model then you also =
lose money when the pound is down, because you have hedging costs when the =
client doesn=E2=80=99t buy and you don=E2=80=99t get reimbursed with the op=
tion premium.
