om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Fracking</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say that you are a giant=
 universal investor and you own 10% of every company in the world. The chie=
f executive officer=C2=A0of one of your portfolio companies, a US oil and g=
as exploration and production business, calls you up and says =E2=80=9Chey,=
 oil prices are really high, I want to drill a bunch of wells and ramp up p=
roduction to sell lots of oil at $120 a barrel, whaddaya think?=E2=80=9D Wh=
at do you think?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are some things that =
you might say to this CEO, specifically because you are a giant universal i=
nvestor and you own 10% of every company in the world:</p><ol style=3D"list=
-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Look: I own 10% of your company, but I also own 10% of=
 every other oil driller. They=E2=80=99re all going to call me up and say t=
he same thing: =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s drill more oil.=E2=80=9D If I say yes=
 to all of them, the volume of oil production will go up, but the price wil=
l go down. Everyone will drill more oil and sell it for less money, and we=
=E2=80=99ll all be worse off. Sure if=C2=A0<em>only you=C2=A0</em>drilled m=
ore oil=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0</em>would make more money, but I own all of your=
 competitors, so I can=E2=80=99t think in those terms. If everyone drilled =
more oil, no one would make more money. And in fact in the last big oil boo=
m, everyone did drill more oil, and it cost public investors like me hundre=
ds of billions of dollars. So, no.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>Look: I own 10% of your company, but I also own 10% of every beachfront ho=
tel company, and of every other company in the world for that matter. More =
oil drilling will make you more money, sure, but it will also cause more gl=
obal warming, which will cause lots of economic destruction and instability=
. As a universal investor, I am paid primarily to think about <em>systemic=
=C2=A0</em>risks, not to care about the operations of any one company. The =
systemic risks to my portfolio=C2=A0from the=C2=A0global warming will be mu=
ch greater than the profits to me from you drilling a bit more=C2=A0oil, so=
 I am philosophically trying to transition all my portfolio companies away =
from fossil-fuel extraction.[1] So, no.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">If there are enough investors like you =E2=80=94=C2=A0enough investors w=
ho own the oil sector as a whole and so don=E2=80=99t want any one player t=
o be undisciplined about production, or enough investors who care about env=
ironmental risks=C2=A0and so get nervous about making long-term investments=
 in oil production =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the CEO will abandon her plans to dr=
ill more oil. After all, you investors are the people who buy her stock, wh=
o approve her bonuses, who will keep her in power if an activist shows up t=
rying to fire her. She wants to do what you want, and if that means drillin=
g less oil (and making less money) then that=E2=80=99s what she=E2=80=99ll =
do. Her ultimate goal is shareholder happiness, not profit maximization.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But an oil company that=C2=A0<em>isn=E2=80=99=
t=C2=A0</em>owned by universal owners =E2=80=94=C2=A0one that is owned by p=
eople whose wealth is concentrated in that single oil company =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0might make different decisions. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/28078080.259603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9mcm=
Fja2luZy1iaWxsaW9uYWlyZS1oYXJvbGQtaGFtbS1wcm9wb3Nlcy1idXlpbmctcmVtYWluZGVyL=
W9mLWNvbnRpbmVudGFsLXJlc291cmNlcy0xMTY1NTIwNzYxNz9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzaiZydT15YWhv=
bw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB80bec626" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">And so</a>:</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Harold Hamm, the billionaire fracking pioneer wh=
o helped launch the U.S. shale boom, is looking to take Continental Resourc=
es Inc. private, offering about $4.3 billion in cash to buy the portion of =
the company=E2=80=99s shares he and his family don=E2=80=99t already own. =
=E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While most of Continental=E2=80=
=99s publicly traded oil-company peers are owned by multiple institutional =
investors, Mr. Hamm, the 13th child of Oklahoma sharecroppers, has retained=
 control of the company he founded in 1967, holding north of 70% of its sha=
res even after it went public in 2007, according to FactSet. =E2=80=A6</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a statement to employees, Mr. Hamm said it n=
o longer makes sense for Continental to be a publicly traded company, citin=
g =E2=80=9Ca lack of support from the public market=E2=80=9D for oil-and-ga=
s companies, evident in the diminishing number of public shale companies du=
e to acquisitions and bankruptcies, and with some going private.</p></block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Financial Times <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28078080.259603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY2=
9tL2NvbnRlbnQvMmFkM2VjYTctYmU2MC00MjBiLWFjODItZDQ1MjFlYTU1NDlh/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBae15dc0d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">elaborates</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Shale baron Harold Hamm has hardly hidden his disdain for W=
all Street=E2=80=99s environmental, social and governance movement, conside=
ring it a leash on companies such as Continental Resources as they try to g=
et on with the job of producing more fossil fuels.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">A climate change =E2=80=9Creligion=E2=80=9D had gripped investors, =
he argued in an interview with the Financial Times last year, and companies=
 such as European supermajor BP were about to =E2=80=9Ccut their [own] thro=
at=E2=80=9D by winding down oil operations under pressure to decarbonise. .=
..</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Analysts said the move could free Contin=
ental to do what public producers have for months been told by Wall Street =
not to: fire up drilling rigs to capitalise on a surge in oil prices to wel=
l above $100 a barrel.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hamm and other publi=
c shale bosses watched as their privately held rivals sharply escalated dri=
lling activity this year, unbothered by institutional investors insisting o=
n scooping up their piece of the windfall.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Executives have often seethed in private about their difficulties in persua=
ding ESG-focused portfolio managers in long-only funds to back more oil and=
 gas exploration.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The obvious =
move here is to blame ESG: ESG-focused public investors don=E2=80=99t want =
to drill for oil, so they hold back oil drillers, but if you go private you=
 can avoid ESG constraints. Shale barons and ESG investors are sort of natu=
ral enemies, so it is no surprise that Hamm doesn=E2=80=99t like ESG.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But we have been <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/28078080.259603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDQtMTYvc2hvdWxkLW11dHVhbC1mdW5kcy1iZS1pbGxl=
Z2FsLT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjE2MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3V=
yY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA2MTYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd3b6da74" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talking for years</a> around here=
 about the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2807808=
0.259603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMT=
ItMDcvcmVndWxhdG9ycy1hc2staWYtaW5kZXgtZnVuZHMtYXJlLWJhZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjE2M=
jJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1f=
dGVybT0yMjA2MTYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc4=
79b9fb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> other possible theory</a>: Index funds that own every (pub=
lic) company in an industry, the theory goes, constrain competition, becaus=
e if everyone ramps up production to steal market share then everybody lose=
s, and universal owners are a way to coordinate to restrict competition and=
 keep margins high. The shale drilling boom is <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28078080.259603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjItMDYtMTQvZml2ZS10aGluZ3MteW91LW5lZWQtdG8ta=
25vdy10by1zdGFydC15b3VyLWRheT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjE2MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVk=
aXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA2MTYmdXRtX2NhbXB=
haWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB09ec30f5" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> an infamou=
s case</a> of how high oil prices led to overinvestment in drilling and ult=
imately to huge losses for investors. Public investors learned that lesson =
really well. =E2=80=9CShale Oil=E2=80=99s Newfound Production Discipline Be=
gins to Pay Off,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/28078080.259603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjEtMTEtMzAvc2hhbGUtb2lsLXMtbmV3Zm91bmQtcHJvZHVjdGlvbi1kaXNjaXBsaW5lLW=
JlZ2lucy10by1wYXktb2ZmP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MTYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09Z=
