ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> said a Bloomberg=
 headline</a> last year. If you own every oil company, it is insane to enco=
urage all of them to drill more wells, not as a climate matter, just as a p=
rofitability matter. But if you own=C2=A0<em>one=C2=A0</em>oil company, tha=
t is the opportunity.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way: If you ar=
e an ESG-focused investor, and you=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>own shares of a pu=
blic oil company, and that oil company=E2=80=99s CEO says =E2=80=9Cbeing ow=
ned by ESG-focused public shareholders is holding us back, I=E2=80=99ve rai=
sed some money, let=E2=80=99s go private=E2=80=9D: Should you vote to appro=
ve the deal?[2] (This is less relevant to Continental, where Hamm=E2=80=99s=
 family owns a large majority of the stock, but it=E2=80=99s a fun general =
question.[3]) On the one hand, if the company goes private, you=C2=A0are (1=
) reducing the carbon emissions of your portfolio and (2) getting bought ou=
t at a premium. On the other hand, you are (1) definitely increasing the am=
ount of carbon emissions=C2=A0<em>in the world</em>, since the company is g=
oing private specifically in order to pollute more, and (2) missing out on =
the profits of doing that. An ESG strategy of =E2=80=9Cwe will own all the =
oil companies, to prevent someone worse from owning the oil companies=E2=80=
=9D makes a weird kind of sense.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-co=
ntent" width=3D"auto" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0">
