-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">FX</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a former life,=C2=A0I used to struc=
ture and market derivatives to corporate clients at Goldman Sachs Group Inc=
. (Disclosure!) Some basic themes of derivatives marketing are:</p><ol styl=
e=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When markets are boring and volatility is low=
, it is easy and customer-friendly to go around to customers and offer to b=
uy some options from them. =E2=80=9CWe will give you cash for the volatilit=
y of your stock, which you weren=E2=80=99t using anyway,=E2=80=9D is the ba=
sic pitch, which is very appealing to customers who are bored because the m=
arket isn=E2=80=99t doing anything. This is, like, covered-call strategies =
for asset owners, or put-writing strategies for corporate stock buybacks, e=
tc.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When markets are scary and vol=
atility is high, it is easy and customer-friendly to go around to customers=
 and offer to sell them some options. =E2=80=9CYou can pay us a little bit =
of money for insurance from this scary market,=E2=80=9D is the basic pitch,=
 which is very appealing to customers who are scared because the market kee=
ps going down.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It is always =
better=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>to ask the customer for a cash payment up fro=
nt. (This makes Method 2 harder.) If you can structure a fee into the produ=
ct without an explicit price, that is better.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">The best derivatives=C2=A0products do not contain, or even hint=
 at, words like =E2=80=9Cderivative=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Coption=E2=80=9D or=
 =E2=80=9Cput=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ccall.=E2=80=9D With the best derivatives=
 products, you walk into the room and have an hourlong meeting with the cli=
ent and discuss the product in detail and they understand it perfectly and =
you shake hands and they look at your business card and say =E2=80=9Cwait y=
ou=E2=80=99re a derivatives salesperson?=E2=80=9D The best products identif=
y the customer=E2=80=99s needs or insecurities and give her a solution to t=
hem that feels simple and natural; sure=C2=A0<em>you </em>know that the thi=
ng is a series of puts and calls that your quants can model, but to the=C2=
=A0<em>client=C2=A0</em>it doesn=E2=80=99t feel that way at all.</li></ol><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In that vein, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/28078080.259603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMTQvZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy1pcy1zZXQtdG8tb2ZmZXItZn=
gtcHJpY2VzLXRoYXQtbGFzdC1mb3ItZGF5cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjE2MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1d=
G1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA2MTYmdXRt=
X2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe2e22813" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I l=
ove this</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman Sachs Gro=
up Inc. is preparing to offer foreign-exchange prices that last for days to=
 help fintechs, airlines and e-commerce firms avoid turbulence in the $6.6 =
trillion-per-day global currency market.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
e Wall Street giant has begun quoting FX rates that last for minutes and pl=
ans to extend this in the coming weeks, according to Abbas Khamisa, executi=
ve director in FX solutions and structuring at the bank. The aim is to help=
 firms hedge risk and protect them from having to do hundreds of transactio=
ns at different rates. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Under Gold=
man=E2=80=99s offering, clients can expect to pay a premium, in the form of=
 an added spread, to reflect the risk that exchange rates move against the =
bank=E2=80=99s position. The bank will vary its prices based on the volumes=
, currency pairs and amount of time the customer needs.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CFirms can request a quote ranging from minutes to hou=
rs, to days, to the weekend and eventually to months, with clients knowing =
exactly how much they are being charged,=E2=80=9D Khamisa said in an interv=
iew. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve had a lot of interest.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=A6<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman=E2=80=99s guaranteed prices are dif=
ferent to forward rates because they give clients the flexibility to trade =
at a set rate rather than requiring them to do so, Khamisa said. =E2=80=9CW=
hen the client has certainty on the timings and notional of their exposure,=
 then they can execute a trade,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThis allows clie=
nts to price their goods and services in multiple currencies, without the c=
hallenges of forecasting and risk managing potential exposures in advance.=
=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One sort of imagines=
 the mandate: =E2=80=9COkay, implied volatility is up, let=E2=80=99s go out=
 and sell some short-dated puts and calls.=E2=80=9D If you go to a client a=
nd say, like, =E2=80=9Chi, are you in the market for a two-hour call option=
 on 10 million pounds,=E2=80=9D they will say =E2=80=9Chuh that sounds like=
 a weird thing, probably not.=E2=80=9D[4] But if you go to the client and s=
ay =E2=80=9Cas your special relationship bank, we will give you a guarantee=
d price on up to 10 million pounds for the next two hours,=C2=A0so you can =
price your goods in multiple currencies without the challenges of forecasti=
ng and risk managing potential exposures in advance, for two hours,=E2=80=
=9D the client will find that very convenient and appreciate your good serv=
ice.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am not sure how pricing works =
exactly, but the way I read this story is that the client is not charged an=
 upfront fee: =E2=80=9CClients can expect to pay a premium, in the form of =
an added spread,=E2=80=9D meaning that you pay for the option only if (and =
to the extent) you exercise it. That is a somewhat nervous-making approach,=
 for the bank. In theory, if you tell the client =E2=80=9Cyou can buy as ma=
ny as 10 million pounds, or as few as zero pounds, for $1.20 each over the =
next hour, and you just pay us an extra $0.001 for each pound you end up bu=
ying,=E2=80=9D[5]=C2=A0then that is effectively a call option on 10 million=
 pounds, struck at $1.201, that you have given away for free. If the pound =
goes above $1.201 during that hour, the client should buy all 10 million po=
unds from you, and you will have lost money; if the pound stays below $1.20=
1, the client should go buy its pounds elsewhere =E2=80=94=C2=A0plenty of b=
anks are happy to sell pounds at the spot price=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and you=
 will not make money.[6] This is a terrible trade, for the bank, if the cli=
ent is a purely rational economic actor.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On=
 the other hand there are good reasons to think the client will not be a pu=
rely rational economic actor. =E2=80=9CThe aim is to help firms hedge risk =
and protect them from having to do hundreds of transactions at different ra=
tes.=E2=80=9D There probably are lots of clients who will happily pay a hig=
her average rate to not have to worry about it. The client is explicitly pa=
ying you for the relief of not having to monitor the FX market. If the poun=
d goes up, the client buys from you and underpays. If the pound goes down, =
the client buys from you and overpays but is happy not to have to think abo=
ut it. If the pound goes up and down and up and down, the client buys from =
you the whole time; sure, the client <em>could </em>buy from you when it=E2=
=80=99s up and from another broker when it=E2=80=99s down, but that is a lo=
t of work, and the client is cheerfully paying you to avoid that work. Just=
 putting the =E2=80=9Chundreds of transactions at different rates=E2=80=9D =
into a spreadsheet is work, and the client will pay something to avoid that=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also of course if some=C2=A0clients do ke=
ep buying from you when the pound is up, and not when it is down, then you =
will stop offering them this service. This is a good-long-term-relationship=
 sort of service, not a series of economically priced options.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still you have to make sure not to sign up the clients=
 who <em>are=C2=A0</em>purely rational economic actors, and who will put in=
 the work to hose you:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tom Auld=
, a Cambridge University academic and former high frequency trader, said th=
e plans would likely suit both sides -- provided clients are meeting corpor=
ate needs and aren=E2=80=99t betting on market moves.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt makes a lot of sense if you=E2=80=99ve got an unsoph=
isticated client who is not going to try and arbitrage the price, and may n=
ot be able to make a quick decision,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CGoldman Sac=
hs will have to be very careful about who they field it to. They won=E2=80=
=99t give it to a hedge fund but they might give it to an SME or some other=
 client that isn=E2=80=99t interested in arbitraging.=E2=80=9D</p></blockqu=
ote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah. If you are a derivatives structurer =
and you say to your boss, =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s write free options to smal=
l corporate clients,=E2=80=9D your boss will hear you out; writing free opt=
ions to small businesses can be lucrative. Nobody lasts long writing free o=
ptions to hedge funds.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" =
cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"center">
