<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Oracle latency</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/28078080.259603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMDEvY3J5cHRvLWNsZWFyaW5nLWFuZC1jcmVkaXQ_Y21w=
aWQ9QkJEMDYxNjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3N=
sZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjE2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cBaa5d1a37" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked a few weeks ago</a> about differences=
 in how the traditional financial system and the crypto financial system tr=
eat leverage. The way the traditional system works is that if you have a ma=
rgin loan, and the value of your collateral declines, your broker calls you=
 up and says =E2=80=9Chey we need more collateral,=E2=80=9D and you either =
post more collateral and it=E2=80=99s fine, or you don=E2=80=99t post more =
collateral and your broker liquidates your position. Or sometimes you say s=
omething like =E2=80=9Chang on I=E2=80=99ve got another call, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28078080.259603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjkvYXJjaGVnb3Mtd2FzLX=
Rvby1idXN5LWZvci1tYXJnaW4tY2FsbHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYxNjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX=
21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjE2JnV0bV9j=
YW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8aa04ac8" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I=E2=
=80=99ll call you back after lunch</a>,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Csorry I don=E2=
=80=99t have the money right now but I am a good customer and you know I=E2=
=80=99m good for it,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t have the money ri=
ght now but I=E2=80=99m pretty sure prices can only recover from here so wh=
y don=E2=80=99t you let it ride for a day or two,=E2=80=9D or whatever, and=
 you <em>don=E2=80=99t </em>post more collateral but your broker=C2=A0<em>d=
oesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>liquidate your position because you=E2=80=99re a h=
uman and your broker is a human and everyone is embedded in a repeated soci=
al game with fuzzy rules. Whereas the way that the crypto system =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0particularly the decentralized finance side of it =E2=80=94=C2=A0work=
s is that if you have a margin loan, and the value of your collateral decli=
nes far enough, a robot liquidates the collateral immediately without even =
bothering to call you.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are adva=
ntages and disadvantages to each approach. We were talking about a proposal=
 from crypto exchange FTX, and I wrote:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Simplistically, you=E2=80=99d expect the FTX model to lead to=C2=
=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>defaults and liquidations, but for those defaults to =
be=C2=A0<em>less bad</em>. In the traditional system, sometimes people will=
 have a =E2=80=9Ctechnical issue,=E2=80=9D and the exchange will =E2=80=9Cg=
ive the appropriate amount of time not to dislocate the market and create a=
 bigger stress on that,=E2=80=9D and it will work out fine =E2=80=94=C2=A0b=
ut occasionally it=C2=A0<em>won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>work out fine, and by d=
elaying the exchange will have caused a much bigger problem.</p></blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Often, delaying liquidation will just make t=
he problem go away: Prices will recover and you won=E2=80=99t have to liqui=
date. Sometimes, delaying liquidation will make the problem worse: Prices w=
ill keep going down, and by the time you liquidate there won=E2=80=99t be e=
nough value left to repay the margin loan.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Part of this is about the fuzziness of the traditional system, but part of =
it is also about measurement times. In traditional finance, often, you get =
margin calls based on the price of your assets at the end of the day, or at=
 some other discrete measuring time. If your stocks go down in the morning =
and back up in the afternoon, you might be undercollateralized at noon, but=
 you never get a margin call because it=E2=80=99s all fine by the time your=
 broker gets around to looking at the report at 4:30. FTX=E2=80=99s proposa=
l, and the crypto ethos generally, is about real-time 24/7 monitoring and a=
utomatic liquidations. I wrote:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>In the traditional system, if the price of corn drops at midnight, and you=
r broker calls you up for more margin, and you don=E2=80=99t post more marg=
in, your broker thinks =E2=80=9Caha you are asleep=E2=80=9D and waits until=
 the morning to call you again. But =E2=80=9Chumans are asleep at midnight=
=E2=80=9D is the sort of off-chain information that a purely algorithmic ap=
proach would ignore.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well! At =
FT Alphaville, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/280=
78080.259603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZDA4ZTJiNTgtMGI0My00ODZkLT=
g5N2YtZDY0MGMxM2FhZGZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB31f97285" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Alexandra=
 Scaggs has a fun post</a> about oracle latency. A large crypto wallet owns=
 a lot of Ethereum, funded by borrowing, and as the price of Ethereum dropp=
ed the account became undercollateralized and should have been liquidated. =
But it wasn=E2=80=99t. Scaggs:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
On Wednesday morning, the price of ether fell below the implied liquidation=
 price. At the time that was said to be around $1,015.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">So what happened? Why didn=E2=80=99t the account get liquidated=
?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As the above tweet explains, it was an is=
sue of =E2=80=9Coracle update latency=E2=80=9D. =E2=80=A6 At risk of oversi=
mplification, an =E2=80=9Coracle=E2=80=9D is essentially a data feed that h=
elps smart contracts perform their function. In this case a service called =
chainlink puts prices on the blockchain so Aave=E2=80=99s smart contracts c=
an use them to operate.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This isn=E2=80=99t =
the futures market, and updating prices on-chain is expensive. So they aren=
=E2=80=99t refreshed in real time. Instead, chainlink updates the on-chain =
prices when the =E2=80=9Coff-chain=E2=80=9D data deviates by 0.5 per cent o=
r more from the latest update, or every hour.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">When ether fell to around $1015, it would have triggered a sizable liqui=
dation if it had met the criteria for the price to go on-chain.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it didn=E2=80=99t. It wasn=E2=80=99t a large enoug=
h move compared to the price recorded in the prior on-chain update, and it =
didn=E2=80=99t last for an hour. So instead of getting blown out of around =
$250mn in ether, the account got to live another day.</p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I dunno. Seems fine? =E2=80=9CWe check the prices e=
very hour, and if you=E2=80=99re undercollateralized at any hourly update w=
e=E2=80=99ll liquidate you=E2=80=9D is kind of a reasonable thing for a bro=
ker to say. As a way to handle financial-market risk, it=E2=80=99s just fin=
e; the lender takes an hour of price risk, which is a lot less than lenders=
 take=C2=A0in a lot of traditional financing businesses. Still it=E2=80=99s=
 not a particularly, like,=C2=A0<em>futuristic=C2=A0</em>thing for the=C2=
=A0broker to say? In the stock market, traders have computers that can chec=
k the price many times each millisecond. In crypto, the computers are famou=
sly slow and expensive, so checking the price every hour is the best they c=
an do.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=
